<taxonomicNameLabel rank="subSpecies">new subspecies</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="130">Text Figure 32</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="130">
Soldier.-Length 4 mm. Differing from the typical form and the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:151214" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole caffra bayeri Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="caffra" subSpecies="bayeri">subspecies bayeri</taxonomicName>
in the sculpture of the head, the sharp longitudinal rugae between the prolonged frontal carinae being surrounded by the rugae from the sides of the head, which run up to the posterior corners, then turn at a right angle and run transversely on the occipital lobes to the occipital furrow. These rugae are quite as strong as those on the front, but denser. The head is a little longer and a little more depressed posteriorly than in the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:180323" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole caffra bayeri var. thysvillensis Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="caffra" variety="thysvillensis">variety thysvillensis</taxonomicName>
, the transverse welt of the mesonotum less pronounced; the blunt epinotal spines distinctly shorter. The sculpture of the thorax and pedicel and the color and pilosity are much as in that variety.
</paragraph>
<caption>
<paragraph pageNumber="131">
<pageStartToken pageNumber="131">Fig-</pageStartToken>
32. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:151216" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole caffra senilifrons Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="caffra" subSpecies="senilifrons">Pheidole caffra subspecies senilifrons</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="subSpecies">new subspecies</taxonomicNameLabel>
. Soldier, a, body in profile; b, head from above.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageNumber="131">
Worker.-Length 1.8 mm. Very similar to the worker 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:180323" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole caffra bayeri var. thysvillensis Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thysvillensis">thysvillensis</taxonomicName>
but the pronotum is smooth and shining and the epinotal spines are shorter, less obtuse, and more erect.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageNumber="131">Four soldiers and a single worker from Yakuhiku, where they were found &quot;nesting in a small mushroom-shaped termitarium&quot; (Lang and Chapin).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
